Lab: User role controlled by request parameter.

Vulnerability: Admin panel access controlled by a forgeable cookie.

Objective: Access admin panel and using it delete the user carlos.

Exploitation Steps:
1. Access the lab and log in with the provided credentials.
2. Connect Burp Suite with browser and in Proxy, turn on Intercept.
3. In the lab, add /admin to the url to access the admin panel and send the request.
4. In Burp Proxy, intercept this request and observe that Admin parameter is set to false.
5. Change this value to true and forward this request. This will open the admin panel successfully.
6. Delete the user carlos from the panel inside lab.
7. Again go to Burp Proxy, intercept the delete request and change the Admin parameter to true.
8. Forward all the remaining requests. This will delete the user and solve the lab.

How it works:
- The application uses the Admin parameter to determine whether a user is an administrator.
- By intercepting the request in Burp Suite, we were able to view and modify the request before it reached the server.
- The Admin value was set to false. Changing it to true tricked the application into treating us as an administrator.
- Since the application trusted a cookie value for access control, it allowed unauthorized access to the admin panel.

Result: We were able to access the admin panel and delete the user carlos.

Risk Involved: An attacker may modify the request and gain unauthorized access to administrative functionality.

Remediation:
- Do not use user-controlled parameters or cookies to determine user roles.
- Validate user permissions on the server side before granting access to administrative functionality.
- Implement proper access control checks for all sensitive endpoints.
- Use secure session management to store and verify user roles.
